translated: Matthias Natanael (Natan), lecturer, Växjö, b. 30/5/98 in Asarum, Blekinge county. Married 1. in 1927 to Sys Poulsen; 2. in 1936 to Lita Walilin. Children: Jan b. 1929, Lena b. 1936, Klas b. 1937, Stefan b. 1944. - Bachelor of Arts in Lund in 1921, Master of Arts in 1922, Licentiate of Philosophy in 1928, Doctor of Philosophy in 1930, promoted in 1931. Assistant at Asine excavation in 1924-1926, external member at École française d'Athènes in 1925-1927, secretary at the Swedish Institute in Rome in 1927, student at the University of Copenhagen in 1929-1930, led own excavations in Messenia in Greece in 1926-1937, studied in Greece, Italy, Yugoslavia, Albania, Egypt, Palestine, Syria, Germany, Austria, Hungary, France, and the Netherlands in 1924-1947. Lecturer at Lund University in 1930-1940, acting professor there in 1930-1932, 1936-1940, at Gothenburg University in 1932, 1936, 1934, lecturer in Hudiksvall in 1940-1945, professor in Lund from 1939, lecturer at the Teacher's Training College in Växjö from 1945. Built and organized the museum in Vasiliko in Greece from 1933-1935. Chairman of the Faculty of Philosophy society in Lund from 1930-1936, initiated the home guard in Skåne in 1940, chairman of the Hudiksvalls home guard association from 1940-1945, started the humanistic society's library in 1943, secretary from 1943-1945, member of the Royal Society of Sciences in Lund from 1936, corresponding member of the German Archaeological Institute in 1937, member of the Commission for Civil Institutions in Athens in 1946. Works: Karlshamn-Asarum (1923), Topographical Studies on Ancient Messenia (1930), Athens in ancient times (1931), A la grecque (1932), Daily life in ancient Athens (1934, Danish edition in 1935), Work and Slavery in Antiquity (1937), Modern Greece (1937), Democracy in ancient Athens (1939), The Swedish Messenia Expedition (1938), Excavations at Delphi III:VI (inscriptions in theaters, 1939), The Adriatic Area etc. (1939), Hellenistic horizon (1941), Alexander the Great (1942, Danish edition in 1943), Hannibal (1944, Danish edition in 1946), By the wine-red sea (1944), The Doric problem (1945), Demosthenes (1946), around 20 scientific articles, around 40 popular scientific journal articles, co-author of the Swedish Encyclopedia and in national and international daily press. Hobbies: landscape painting, stamp collecting. Knight of the Order of Vasa in 1936, Commander of the Order of the North Star in 1947, honorary citizen of Vasiliko in Greece in 1933, Home Guard's gold plaque in 1942. Axel Ruben Natanael, dentist, Sölvesborg, b. 8/1/87 in Hässleholm, son of falbr. Axel Israel W. 0. Maria Andersson. Married in 1913 to Jenny Wessiberg. Children: Aino b. 1914, died in 1918. Margaretha b. 1915, Carl-Gustav b. 1917, Carl-Axel b. 1918, Börje b. 1920, Birgitta b. 1922, died in 1929, Gudrun b. 1924. - Graduated from Christianstad in 1906, dentistry degree in 1909, dentist in 1911. Bank clerk in 1906-1908, dental practitioner in Sölvesborg since 1911, school dentist there in 1929-1944. Board member of the Swedish Dental Association in 1928-1931, vice chairman in 1931-1936 and chairman in 1936-1946. Member of the county board of health and the board of Sölvesborg Spirits Limited since 1928. Studied in Germany in 1915.
